TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Conditioning Effect of Time on Firm Survival: An Industry Life Cycle Approach
AU  - Agarwal, Ratshree
AU  - Sarkar, MB
AU  - echambadi, Raj
Y1  - 2002/10/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069325
DO  - 10.5465/3069325
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 971
EP  - 994
VL  - 45
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In an effort to reconcile theoretical ?blind spots,? we integrated research in technology management, organizational ecology, and evolutionary economics. The central premise underlying the resultant model is that time conditions the effects of age, contemporaneous size, order of entry, and contemporaneous density on mortality rates. We tested our hypotheses using a life cycle approach and data on 33 product innovations that span most of the 20th century. Results resoundingly support our central thesis on the impact of time on both survival rates and relationships previously thought to be universalistic.
AB  - In an effort to reconcile theoretical ?blind spots,? we integrated research in technology management, organizational ecology, and evolutionary economics. The central premise underlying the resultant model is that time conditions the effects of age, contemporaneous size, order of entry, and contemporaneous density on mortality rates. We tested our hypotheses using a life cycle approach and data on 33 product innovations that span most of the 20th century. Results resoundingly support our central thesis on the impact of time on both survival rates and relationships previously thought to be universalistic.
