TY  - JOUR
T1  - New Product Search Over Time: Past Ideas in Their Prime?
AU  - Katila, Riitta
Y1  - 2002/10/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069326
DO  - 10.5465/3069326
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 995
EP  - 1010
VL  - 45
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study is an investigation of how the age of the knowledge that firms search affects how innovative they are. Two seemingly contradictory propositions are examined: (1) old knowledge hurts by making innovation activities obsolete and (2) old knowledge helps because its reliability and legitimacy promote innovation. Results based on longitudinal data on 131 robotics firms reconcile the contradictory propositions: while old intraindustry knowledge hurts, old extraindustry knowledge promotes innovation.
AB  - This study is an investigation of how the age of the knowledge that firms search affects how innovative they are. Two seemingly contradictory propositions are examined: (1) old knowledge hurts by making innovation activities obsolete and (2) old knowledge helps because its reliability and legitimacy promote innovation. Results based on longitudinal data on 131 robotics firms reconcile the contradictory propositions: while old intraindustry knowledge hurts, old extraindustry knowledge promotes innovation.
